etymologies: late 19th century. From ancient Greek ἑν-, stem of εἷς (masculine) one + τριάκοντα thirty + -ane, after German Hentriacontan

definitions: Any of a number of hydrocarbons of the alkane series having thirty-one carbon atoms, especially the unbranched isomer (also "n-hentriacontane"), a waxy solid present in petroleum and various natural waxes.
